    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1917-03-21T12:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1917-03-21T12:00:00-05:00" n="778"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d778">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 763.72/3567</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister in Sweden</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_MIN1"
                        type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Morris</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Stockholm</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1917-03-21T18:00:00+01:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">March 21, 1917, 6 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                        <lb/> [<hi rend="italic">Received March 22, 3 a.m.</hi>]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>246. Referring to the Department’s 137<note n="1" xml:id="d778fn1">See No. 268 to
                        Denmark, <hi rend="italic">ante</hi>, <ref target="#pg_550">p.
                        550</ref>.</note> and circular March 16, 2 p.m. Foreign Minister told me
                    to-day he was authorized give <pb facs="0727" n="555" xml:id="pg_555"/> verbal
                    Swedish neutrality rules. Contained no mention of armed merchant vessels, and
                    that for the present Swedish Government was unable make any definite decision,
                    but reserved the right to treat each case separately later in conference. I drew
                    from Foreign Minister the statement that for the present armed American merchant
                    vessels, whether armed by the Government or by the owners, would be allowed
                    freely to enter and depart from Swedish ports as heretofore. In reply to my
                    inquiry the Minister for Foreign Affairs <hi rend="italic">confidentially</hi>
                    stated that Sweden did not care to set a precedent on this question at present,
                    but preferred to await developments, and that in not definitely committing
                    themselves at present, Sweden obviated what might lead to some embarrassment
                    with neighboring countries. I learned to-day from high Swedish official that
                    Danish representative will make a similar reply.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_MIN1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Morris</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
